content.description: The route starts in a dihedral behind a small pine. Then up a couple terraces to a steeper top. A good route for new lead climbers.

Head up a set of steps then move up onto the more vertical face with some slopey holds in horizontal seams.

Traverse right at the end to anchor slighty around the corner.
content.protection: 4 bolts and chain achor shared with Papa Smurf.
content.location:
As you come out of the trees from the cairn trail, this route will be right in front of you.

This is the route on the left of this side of the wall.

content.description:
At the start I climbed up on the ledge to the right of the route and reached over left to clipped the first bolt by my feet. Not sure if this would be the normal way to start this route? Anyway, move onto the face and go up through a bulge and couple of small roofs using horizontal crack jugs and good crimps with pretty good feet most of the time.

I found a cruxy section in the middle and another crux pulling up to the anchor.
content.location: this the route on the far right of the part of the wall that you are looking at as you walk up out of the trees from the cairn trail.

content.description: Climb the corner by bolt line using features to the right.Crux is near the anchors.If you climb left of bolt line it is 10b.
Climb up slot to first bolt.Then its the bolt line to the left under the larger end of the roof.The crux can be cheated by standing on ledge to the left of roof.
content.location: First route on right of rock outcrop in the middle of the wall.

content.description: A short but fun route with closely placed bolts for the beginning leader.. (The second bolt is Moot for climbers comfortable at the grade.)designed and put up by Zach, His first route, first ascent,and lead. Keep that in mind when you're at the third bolt.. keep it easy,, and enjoy..
content.protection: 7-8 Bolts to chain anchor. (two foot runners to clean anchors)
content.location: the farthest right route on the wall

content.description:
This route was bolted with beginning leaders in mind.

It's slabby with some some good jugs, bolts pretty close together.

The crux is probably clipping the anchor.
content.location:
When you arrive at the wall after following the cairn trial these routes will be on your far left, around the corner and up and a set of quartzite steps.

Of the two routes, this one is on the left.

content.description: Start on boulder on right side of big roof. Follow white camo bolt hangers out on face to your left. Save some energy for clipping the anchors.

This is a very fun juggy route on great rock with good feet the whole way.

Start under the roof. Pull up right of the roof on great jugs. The route then tends left to the anchor, which is shared with Sponge Bob.
content.location:
As you come out of the trees from the cairn trail, this route will be right in front of you.

This is the route the middle route of this side of the wall.

content.description: The one puzzle piece is between the 3rd and 4th bolt. Then its easier climbing to the chains. Great route for moderate climbers.
One fine nine. Very sustained. great worm up for the harder routes.
content.location: Starts about 15 feet left of the big roof.

content.description: A fun 10b with a hard boulder start.
content.location: on the left side of the big roof.

content.description: This route was bolted with the beginning leader in mind. Still, you have to think about the feet a time or two and it has mantle in the middle and easier finish than the route to the left of it.
content.location:
When you arrive at the wall after following the cairn trial these routes will be on your far left, around the corner and up and a set of quartzite steps.

Of the two routes, this one on the right.

content.description: Route starts through a crevice then climbs a challenging face to a small roof. Anchors above roof. Shares first bolt and anchors with Saturday the 14th on the left of it.very fun,must do route.
content.location: just right of rock outcrop in middle of wall.

content.description:
I originally thought this route was Bloodsucker, nice crack with bolts to the left of it, and anchors at the top, but I was informed by one of the brothers that bolted most of the routes on this wall that this is NOT Bloodsucker, they had put the anchors on it and TR'ed it, but since I lead it, I could name it. So here it is.

Nice crack with a mellow beginning, has a small roof with some good hand jams, and finish with a mantle up onto a nice ledge. Plenty of face holds as well on the way up. There is a small cave at the bottom of this route, which has a nice cool breeze flowing from it. Great place to store beverages while climbing up here.
content.protection: Chains connected with a huge ring on top. Standard rack up to 4" will suffice.
content.location: It's the crack directly to the right of Slow Dance with Liberty, the two routes share the same start.

content.description: Climb up about 10 feet and stand on ledge. Crack starts at about head high. Not hard to see it goes straight up the wall.A fun  natural line that's been violated by clumsy sqeezjob'n.A poor apology for bolting the left side of a crack! It seems.

This route starts in a V slot using a boulder to scramble up to gain the slot, (the slot seems more tricky than it looks) The route mellows out in the middle section with good holds and good feet until it gains the short vertical section at the last two bolts.. Staying left of the last bolt keeps the rating at 5.9.. going right feels harder than 5.9 to get to the anchors,  but that's my opinion.. I would give it more stars if it was more sustained, but I don't see how it could have been bolted better..
content.location: The 4th bolted line from the right... The 12th from the left..
